 {"id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2","title":"[STUB][Track B] WASM boundary convergence and completion","description":"## Background\nThe repo currently has two browser-boundary crates with overlapping intent: `asupersync-browser-core` already contains real export/error/type logic and is in the workspace, while `asupersync-wasm` still advertises the boundary but leaves its key modules as comments. That is a classic duplicate-placeholder situation.\n\n## Scope\n- Decide which crate owns the canonical JS/WASM boundary.\n- Eliminate the misleading split-brain state.\n- Close the remaining export/type/error/package validation gaps for the surviving boundary.\n\n## Why this matters\nA stale second boundary crate is worse than a missing crate because it suggests a supported surface that is not actually live.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Exactly one crate is the canonical owner of the browser export boundary.\n2. The non-canonical surface is either reduced to an honest forwarding/internal role or otherwise made non-misleading without deleting files ad hoc.\n3. Export, error, type, packaging, and consumer validation work all route through the chosen owner.","notes":"Coordinate conceptually with epic `asupersync-3qv04`, but do not assume that epic must close first. The task here is truthfulness and convergence of the boundary ownership model.\n\nValidation charter:\n- Every child implementation bead in this track must finish with comprehensive unit coverage for happy-path, edge-case, boundary, and failure-path behavior.\n- Every child implementation bead that changes runtime-observable behavior must also land at least one deterministic E2E or integration script that exercises the real workflow and the most important failure modes.\n- Validation artifacts for this track must emit structured logs with, at minimum: `scenario_id`, touched feature/profile flags, seed or fixture id, config snapshot, exact command, expected outcome, observed outcome, and artifact/replay pointers.","status":"open","priority":1,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:21:29.597846972Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T01:59:01.858510414Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2","depends_on_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:21:29.597846972Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.1","title":"[STUB][B1] Choose canonical owner for the JS/WASM boundary crates","description":"## Background\n`asupersync-browser-core` is already the real workspace-owned browser boundary, while `asupersync-wasm` still claims the same role with comment-only `exports.rs`, `error.rs`, and `types.rs`. This bead chooses the canonical owner and the exact fate of the duplicate.\n\n## Technical approach\n- Inventory all workspace/package/release consumers of both crates.\n- Choose one canonical public owner for the JS/WASM boundary.\n- Specify whether the other crate becomes a thin forwarder, internal wrapper, packaging shell, or explicitly non-canonical artifact.\n- Define the no-deletion-compliant transition path.\n\n## Test / validation plan\n- Verify there is no remaining split ownership of ABI/export/type/error responsibilities.\n- Confirm the chosen ownership model is compatible with existing Browser Edition packaging.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Canonical ownership of the JS/WASM boundary is frozen.\n2. The non-canonical crate has an explicit honest role.\n3. Downstream implementation bead B2 has a clear target surface.","notes":"The main optimization here is to avoid building two competing boundaries. Convergence is more important than choosing a particular winner.\n\nDownstream validation contract:\n- This decision bead must leave its downstream implementation beads with explicit requirements for comprehensive unit tests, deterministic E2E or integration scripts, and structured validation logs.\n- Any scope or contract decision made here must be reflected in those downstream validation obligations so later implementers do not have to infer the test story.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:24:56.646263501Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T03:02:36.246065513Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T03:02:36.245586432Z","close_reason":"Canonical JS/WASM boundary ownership is now explicit in crate metadata and Browser Edition docs: asupersync-browser-core is canonical; asupersync-wasm is retained non-canonical scaffold.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.1","depends_on_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.1.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:29:35.668119407Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.1","depends_on_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:24:56.646263501Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
 {"id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.2","title":"[STUB][B2] Complete exports, errors, and types on the surviving WASM boundary","description":"## Background\nAfter B1, the surviving boundary must actually own concrete exports, error mapping, and ABI types, while the non-canonical surface must stop pretending to be a second unfinished boundary.\n\n## Technical approach\n- Implement or forward the concrete `exports.rs`, `error.rs`, and `types.rs` surface according to B1.\n- Remove comment-only placeholder behavior from the public-facing boundary modules.\n- Ensure the duplicate crate's remaining role is explicit and non-misleading.\n\n## Test / validation plan\n- Unit tests for export/error/type helpers on host and wasm-facing paths.\n- Targeted Browser Edition build checks for the chosen boundary owner.","acceptance_criteria":"1. No canonical boundary module remains comment-only.\n2. Export/error/type logic is concrete and wired through one owner.\n3. The duplicate surface is honest about its role.\n4. Comprehensive unit tests cover the changed happy paths, edge cases, boundary conditions, and failure paths introduced by this bead.\n5. Deterministic E2E or integration script coverage exists for the user-visible or cross-component workflow changed by this bead, with structured logs capturing `scenario_id`, feature/profile flags, seed or fixture id, config snapshot, exact command, expected outcome, observed outcome, and artifact or replay pointers.","notes":"This bead is allowed to centralize functionality aggressively. What it must not do is keep two half-owners alive.","status":"closed","priority":1,"issue_type":"feature","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:24:58.048843800Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T03:15:46.535106136Z","closed_at":"2026-04-03T03:15:46.534625883Z","close_reason":"Canonical browser boundary remains in asupersync-browser-core; asupersync-wasm now exposes concrete retained-scaffold status/error/fail-closed helpers, has standalone Cargo workspace metadata, local manifest+fmt checks pass, and rch-offloaded lib tests pass. Manifest-path cargo check now reaches real compilation and is blocked only by unrelated root asupersync dead_code errors.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.2","depends_on_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:24:58.048843800Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""},{"issue_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.2","depends_on_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.1","type":"blocks","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:29:37.350425905Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}]}
-{"id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.3","title":"[STUB][B3] Validate packaging, build, and consumer story for the canonical WASM boundary","description":"## Background\nA truthful boundary owner still needs proof that it builds, packages, and is consumable the way the project claims. This bead closes that packaging/consumer loop.\n\n## Technical approach\n- Validate Cargo/workspace/package manifests against the chosen ownership model.\n- Run browser-targeted build checks and package smoke tests.\n- Add or update consumer-facing validation so release artifacts cannot regress back to a placeholder boundary.\n\n## Test / validation plan\n- wasm target build gates.\n- package/consumer smoke checks for the supported browser path.\n- Regression tests for any forwarding shim introduced by B1/B2.","acceptance_criteria":"1. Build and packaging validation matches the chosen boundary owner.\n2. Consumer smoke checks cover the surviving public boundary.\n3. Browser boundary regressions are detectable before release.\n4. Comprehensive unit tests cover the changed happy paths, edge cases, boundary conditions, and failure paths introduced by this bead.\n5. Deterministic E2E or integration script coverage exists for the user-visible or cross-component workflow changed by this bead, with structured logs capturing `scenario_id`, feature/profile flags, seed or fixture id, config snapshot, exact command, expected outcome, observed outcome, and artifact or replay pointers.","notes":"Use this bead to stitch the convergence work back into the existing Browser Edition release story without claiming a second product lane.","status":"in_progress","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:24:59.421133779Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-04-03T03:17:08.854514688Z","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2.3","depends_on_id":"asupersync-v2ofj7.2","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-04-03T01:24:59.421133779Z